\begin_layout Standard
Inaccuracy and imprecision cause two different types of errors: systematic
 and random errors respectively.
 
\emph on
Random errors
\emph default
 or, equivalently, 
\emph on
statistical errors
\emph default
 are the result of uncontrollable random processes involved in the measurement.
 Examples include electrical noise, radioactive decays and reaction times
 (as in timing something with a stopwatch etc.).
 These errors benefit from averaging: when a measurement is repeated sometimes
 the random errors will produce a value larger than the true value, but
 other times they will produce a value smaller than the true value.
 Averaging together multiple repetitions washes out the individual fluctuations
 and produces a more certain estimate of the true value.
 The general rule of thumb is that the mean of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 independent repetitions of a measurement with an error of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta x$
\end_inset

 has an error of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta x/\sqrt{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Much more on this later.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Systematic errors
\emph default
 are those that affect all repetitions of a measurement equally and hence
 do not average out.
 They are the result of factors which could be corrected if they were known
 about, for example: miscalibrated measuring equipment, unaccounted for
 environmental effects, misalignments etc.
 Finding and eliminating systematic errors is essentially the craft of experimen
tal physics.
 An undiagnosed systematic error means you are not really measuring what
 you think you are, which can lead to potentially serious consequences.
 A parable and a modern day case study will amply illustrate the point.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The parable tells of a man who wanted to measure the height of the emperor
 of China.
 So he travelled through China asking each person what they though the height
 of the emperor was.
 We suppose they all know the height of the emperor to a precision of at
 least 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta x=\pm1\ \mathrm{m}$
\end_inset

.
 If our researcher asks 
\begin_inset Formula $n=1\,000\,000\,000$
\end_inset

 people then the standard logic dictates that averaging their results gives
 an error in the mean of
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "JAYNESBOOK"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\Delta x}{\sqrt{n}}=3\times10^{-5}\ \mathrm{m}=0.03\ \mathrm{mm}!
\]

\end_inset

This result is clearly absurd.
 No one would call this a good way of measuring the height of the emperor
 of China.
 Surely most of the people polled have never even seen the emperor! However,
 a common folklore would have grown up around him as people told and discussed
 stories of their emperor
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This is common.
 To this day people persist in the illusion that Napoleon Bonaparte was
 short.
 He was average height for the time.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 This measurement is thus a very precise measurement 
\emph on
of the folklore
\emph default
, but not of the actual height of the emperor.
 There is a systematic error propagated through the entire population which
 causes an illusion of the emperor distinct from the reality.
 The only way to obtain an accurate measurement of the emperor is to find
 the man himself and measure him.
 Of course, this is consistent with all common sense and probability theory.
 Only a failure to distinguish the different types of errors leads to the
 wrong interpretation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our case study is 
\noun on
OPERA
\noun default
: an experiment at the Gran Sasso Laboratory in Italy which measures a beam
 of neutrinos produced at the SPS proton accelerator at CERN in Geneva,
 730 km away (the beam goes through the ground: neutrinos are very weakly
 interacting particles, and pass through the Earth almost like it is not
