\begin_layout Standard
There are some other special types of errors worth mentioning.
 
\emph on
Digitisation error
\emph default
 results from the limited precision of a decimal approximation to a real
 number.
 For example, suppose you are reading a digital voltmeter with the display
 format 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{XXX.XX}$
\end_inset

.
 Since the device can only display two digits after the decimal point the
 remaining digits of the true value must be rounded in some way.
 Different devices can do the rounding differently but you would generally
 expect 
\begin_inset Formula $0.004999\cdots$
\end_inset

 to round down and 
\begin_inset Formula $0.005000\cdots$
\end_inset

 to round up (this is by far the most common rounding method, but it is
 not universal).
 Assuming this is the rounding method then we know that a reading of 
\begin_inset Formula $123.45$
\end_inset

 volts corresponds to a true value between 
\begin_inset Formula $123.445$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $123.455$
\end_inset

.
 Thus we report the reading as the central value 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm$
\end_inset

 the difference between the central and the extremes
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
There is a case to be made for dividing the digitisation error by 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{3}$
\end_inset

 before quoting it.
 This gives 
\begin_inset Formula $123.450\pm0.003$
\end_inset

 in the present case.
 The reasoning behind this will be discussed in the Advanced Topics section.
 For this course do not divide the error.
\end_layout

\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula $123.450\pm0.005$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Rounding error
\emph default
 is a related form of error when you round of results at an intermediate
 stage of calculation.
 Rounding errors compound with each step of the calculation and numerical
 accuracy can be killed with surprisingly few stages of rounding.
 So take this advice: keep as many digits as possible in the intermediate
 stages of a computation, and only round of to a reasonable few at the final
 stage of reporting your results.
 Even better is to organise your calculations such that the minimum number
 of steps is required.
 For example, derive as many the quantities of interest as possible as analytica
l formulae involving the things you immediately measure, and only substitute
 in the numerical values at the last stage.
 There are other tricks for organising your algebra.
 For example, if you need to compute a third order polynomial function 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)=a+bx+cx^{2}+dx^{3}$
\end_inset

 don't do it as written (which involves six multiplications and three additions).
 Instead rearrange the computation as 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)=a+x\left(b+x\left(c+dx\right)\right)$
\end_inset

 which only involves three multiplications and three additions.
 Generally if the expressions have a lot of structure or repeating patterns
 they can be rearranged in some way to reduce the number of steps.
\end_layout

